{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627105"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:45:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:45:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17104"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17104"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.56,0.05,0,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77860"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9794"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63365"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26659"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77860"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENoradrenaline is a key neurotransmitter in the sympathetic nervous system that is synthesised in sympathetic nerve terminals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first step in noradrenaline synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conversion of dopamine to noradrenaline","Conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase","Conversion of L-DOPA to dopamine","Packaging of noradrenaline into vesicles","Uptake of tyrosine into nerve terminals"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first and rate-limiting step in noradrenaline synthesis is the \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E. This enzyme requires tetrahydrobiopterin as a cofactor and molecular oxygen as a substrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of dopamine to noradrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E represents the third step in the synthetic pathway and is catalysed by dopamine \u03b2-hydroxylase.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of L-DOPA to dopamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the second step in the pathway and is catalysed by DOPA decarboxylase.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPackaging of noradrenaline into vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after the synthesis is complete via the vesicular monoamine transporter.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUptake of tyrosine into nerve terminals\u003C/strong\u003E must occur before synthesis can begin but is not part of the synthetic pathway itself.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter synthesis, noradrenaline is packaged into synaptic vesicles by the vesicular monoamine transporter (VMAT) and stored until release is triggered by nerve impulses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Noradrenaline is synthesised from tyrosine through a series of enzymatic reactions in sympathetic nerve terminals.","The rate-limiting step in noradrenaline synthesis is the conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase.","Noradrenaline is stored in synaptic vesicles and released by calcium-dependent exocytosis."],"references":["Rao F, Zhang L, Wessel J, et al. Tyrosine hydroxylase, the rate-limiting enzyme in catecholamine biosynthesis: discovery of common human genetic variants governing transcription, autonomic activity, and blood pressure in vivo. Circulation. 2007;116(9):993-1006. doi:10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.106.682302","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63365"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17104"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63365"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T18:56:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T18:57:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9794"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77860"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdA